-NSnyQAhHz93PunWunfs.description: Gordon Ramsay's version of the classic steak dish – a showstopping centrepiece on a special occasions
directions: Heat oven to 220C/fan 200C/gas 7.

Sit the 1kg beef fillet on a roasting tray, brush with 1 tbsp olive oil and season with pepper, then roast for 15 mins for medium-rare or 20 mins for medium. When the beef is cooked to your liking, remove from the oven to cool, then chill in the fridge for about 20 mins.

While the beef is cooling, chop 250g chestnut (and wild, if you like) mushrooms as finely as possible so they have the texture of coarse breadcrumbs. You can use a food processor to do this, but make sure you pulse-chop the mushrooms so they don’t become a slurry.
Heat 2 tbsp of the olive oil and 50g butter in a large pan and fry the mushrooms on a medium heat, with 1 large sprig fresh thyme, for about 10 mins stirring often, until you have a softened mixture.
Season the mushroom mixture, pour over 100ml dry white wine and cook for about 10 mins until all the wine has been absorbed. The mixture should hold its shape when stirred.
Remove the mushroom duxelle from the pan to cool and discard the thyme.
Overlap two pieces of cling film over a large chopping board. Lay 12 slices prosciutto on the cling film, slightly overlapping, in a double row.
Spread half the duxelles over the prosciutto, then sit the fillet on it and spread the remaining duxelles over.
Use the cling film’s edges to draw the prosciutto around the fillet, then roll it into a sausage shape, twisting the ends of cling film to tighten it as you go.
Chill the fillet while you roll out the pastry.
Dust your work surface with a little flour. Roll out a third of the 500g pack of puff pastry to a 18 x 30cm strip and place on a non-stick baking sheet.
Roll out the remainder of the 500g pack of puff pastry to about 28 x 36cm.
Unravel the fillet from the cling film and sit it in the centre of the smaller strip of pastry.
Beat the 2 egg yolks with 1 tsp water and brush the pastry’s edges, and the top and sides of the wrapped fillet.
Using a rolling pin, carefully lift and drape the larger piece of pastry over the fillet, pressing well into the sides.
Trim the joins to about a 4cm rim. Seal the rim with the edge of a fork or spoon handle.
Glaze all over with more egg yolk and, using the back of a knife, mark the beef Wellington with long diagonal lines taking care not to cut into the pastry.
Chill for at least 30 mins and up to 24 hrs. Heat oven to 200C/fan 180C/gas 6.
Brush the Wellington with a little more egg yolk and cook until golden and crisp – 20-25 mins for medium-rare beef, 30 mins for medium. Allow to stand for 10 mins before serving in thick slices.
ingredients: a good beef fillet (preferably Aberdeen Angus) of around 1kg/2lb 4oz
250g/9oz chestnut mushroom, include some wild ones if you like
500g/1lb 2oz pack puff pastry, thawed if frozen
2 egg yolks beaten with 1 tsp water
-NSnyQAhHz93PunWunfs.name: Beef wellington

-NSt5b_pqbzUQi0HkXQ-.description: this dish is so common and iconic among Koreans that we simply call it “kimchi.” When people talk about kimchi, this is the side dish they’re referring to, despite the fact that there are many kinds of kimchi in Korean cuisine, and many made with napa cabbage, too.
directions: If the cabbage cores stick out too much, trim them off with your knife over your cutting board.

To split a cabbage in half without shredding the densely packed leaves inside, first cut a short slit in the base of the cabbage, enough to get a grip on either half, and then gently pull the halves apart so the cabbage splits open.
Cut a slit through the core of each half, 2 inches above the stem. You want the cabbage leaves to be loose but still attached to the core.

Dunk the halves in a large basin of water to get them wet. Sprinkle salt between the leaves by lifting up every leaf and getting salt in there. Use more salt closer to the stems, where the leaves are thicker.

Let the cabbages rest for 2 hours. Turn over every 30 minutes, so they get well salted. From time to time you can ladle some of the salty water from the bottom of the basin over top of the cabbages if you want to.

After 2 hours, wash the cabbage halves a few times under cold running water. Giving them a good washing, to remove the salt and any dirt. As you wash, split the halves into quarters along the slits you cut into earlier. Cut off the cores, give them a final rinse, and put them in a strainer over a basin so they can drain well.

Combine the water and the sweet rice flour in a small pot. Mix well with a wooden spoon and let it cook over medium heat for about 10 minutes until it starts to bubble. Add the sugar and cook 1 more minute, stirring. Remove from the heat and let it cool off completely.

Pour cooled porridge into a large mixing bowl. Add garlic, ginger, onion, fish sauce, fermented salted shrimp, and hot pepper flakes. Mix well with the wooden spoon until the mixture turns into a thin paste.
Add the radish, carrot, and green onion, plus the Asian chives (or more green onions) and the water dropwort if you’re using them. Mix well.

In a large bowl, spread some kimchi paste on each cabbage leaf. When every leaf in a quarter is covered with paste, wrap it around itself into a small packet, and put into your jar, plastic container, or onggi.
Eat right away, or let it sit for a few days to ferment.

The kimchi will start fermenting a day or two at room temperature, depending on the temperature and humidity of your room. The warmer and more humid it is, the faster the kimchi will ferment. Once it starts to ferment it will smell and taste sour, and pressing on the top of the kimchi with a spoon will release bubbles from beneath. If you’re using a sealed jar with a lid, be sure to open it once a while, let it breathe, and press down on the top of the kimchi.
Once it starts to fermented, store in the refrigerator to use as needed. This slows down the fermentation process, which will make the kimchi more and more sour as time goes on.
ingredients: ½ cup Kosher salt (2.5 ounces: 72 grams)
2 tablespoons sweet rice flour (glutinous rice flour)
2 tablespoons turbinado sugar (or brown or white sugar)
2 cups Korean radish matchsticks (or daikon radish)
1 cup chopped Asian chives (buchu), optional (substitute with 3 green onions, chopped)
½ cup garlic cloves (24 garlic cloves), minced
¼ cup fermented salted shrimp (saeujeot) with the salty brine, chopped
-NSt5b_pqbzUQi0HkXQ-.name: Napa Cabbage Kimchi

-NSt74fb_K_Gx9we7LC7.description: This potato salad recipe is for the traditional creamy type of potato salad, with eggs, celery, and relish. It's perfect for making ahead to let the flavors develop.
directions: Gather all ingredients.
Bring a large pot of salted water to a boil. Add potatoes and cook until tender but still firm, about 15 minutes.
Drain, cool, peel, and chop potatoes.
While potatoes cook, place eggs in a saucepan and cover with cold water. Bring water to a boil; cover, remove from heat, and let eggs stand in hot water for 10 to 12 minutes.
Remove from hot water, cool, peel, and chop eggs.
Combine the potatoes, eggs, celery, onion, relish, mayonnaise, mustard, garlic salt, celery salt, and pepper in a large bowl. Mix together well and refrigerate until chilled.
-NSt74fb_K_Gx9we7LC7.name: Old-Fashioned Potato Salad

directions: In a heavy deep skillet or deep-fryer, heat oil to 360 degrees F (180 degrees C). Oil should be about 1 1/2 inches deep.

In a medium saucepan, heat water and margarine to a rolling boil. Combine the flour and salt; stir into the boiling mixture. Reduce heat to low and stir vigorously until the mixture forms a ball, about 1 minute. Remove from heat and beat in the eggs one at a time. Spoon the mixture into a pastry bag fitted with a large star tip.

Carefully squeeze out 4 inch long strips of dough directly into the hot oil. Fry 3 or 4 strips at once, until golden brown, about 2 minutes on each side. Remove from hot oil to drain on paper towels. Stir together the sugar and cinnamon; roll churros in the mixture while still hot.

-NnEHh4lmv4jpa2-jWUX.description:
An omelette is a versatile and popular dish made from beaten eggs cooked with various ingredients, typically folded or rolled. This simple yet delicious dish is a staple in breakfast and brunch menus around the world. Here's a brief description of an omelette:

The base of an omelette is created by whisking eggs, usually two or three, until well combined. This mixture is then seasoned with salt and pepper to enhance flavor. The eggs are poured into a heated, greased pan, where they cook quickly. As the eggs set around the edges, a spatula is used to gently lift the cooked portions, allowing the uncooked egg to flow underneath.

The magic of the omelette lies in its versatility, as it can be customized with an array of ingredients to suit personal preferences. Common additions include diced vegetables such as bell peppers, onions, tomatoes, and mushrooms. Protein options like diced ham, bacon, or cooked sausage are also popular. Cheese is a common inclusion, adding a rich and gooey texture to the omelette.

Once the eggs are mostly set but still slightly runny on top, the chosen fillings are evenly distributed over one half of the omelette. The other half is then carefully folded over the fillings, creating a half-moon or folded shape. The omelette is allowed to cook for a little longer to ensure that the fillings are heated through and the eggs are fully cooked.

Omelettes can be enjoyed on their own or served with accompaniments such as toast, hash browns, or a side salad. The dish is appreciated not only for its delicious taste but also for its quick preparation and adaptability to various tastes and dietary preferences.
directions: If you're adding vegetables, meat, or cheese to your omelette, chop or prepare them beforehand.
Crack the eggs into a bowl.
Whisk the eggs thoroughly until well combined.
Season with salt and pepper to taste. You can also add a splash of milk or cream for a creamier texture, if desired.
Place a non-stick skillet or frying pan over medium heat.
Add a small amount of butter or cooking oil and let it melt, coating the bottom of the pan.
Pour the whisked eggs into the heated pan, ensuring an even spread.
Allow the eggs to set around the edges. As the edges firm up, gently lift them with a spatula, tilting the pan to let the uncooked egg flow underneath.
Once the edges are set and the center is slightly runny, add your chosen fillings on one half of the omelette.
Carefully fold the other half of the omelette over the fillings, creating a half-moon shape.
Allow the omelette to cook for a bit longer, ensuring the fillings are heated through and the eggs are fully cooked but still moist.
Using the spatula, carefully slide the omelette onto a plate.
Serve the omelette hot, optionally garnished with additional herbs, cheese, or a dollop of sour cream.
ingredients: Eggs: Typically 2-3 eggs per omelette, depending on your preference and hunger.
Fillings of your choice (vegetables, cheese, meat, etc.)
Butter or cooking oil for greasing the pan
-NnEHh4lmv4jpa2-jWUX.name: Omlette Yummy
